In this case it looks like you only need `vi`, which is provided by the default sampler state here: https://github.com/TuringLang/Turing.jl/blob/614f593424f54f458f992ebe81454c29215f28fc/src/inference/Inference.jl#L528

You can remove this `NSState` stuff and just use `SamplerState`.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 8, 0, 38, 18, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'cpfiffer', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467338934, 'comment_body': "You probably need almost none of this code -- it duplicates everything in `NestedSamplers`. You should redo this to just do something like

```julia
function AbstractMCMC.sample_init!(    
	
Attach files by dragging & dropping, selecting or pasting them.
    rng::AbstractRNG,
    model::Model,   ## check `NestedModel`?
    spl::Sampler{<:NS},    ## `Nested{T,B}` ## s == spl ## or `Sampler{<:NS{space, T, P, B}}`
    N::Integer,
    verbose::Bool=true,
    resume_from=nothing,
    debug::Bool = false;
    kwargs...
) where {T, P, B}
    # You need to make a `NestedModel` somehow
    # spl.nested is what I imagine you'd call `Nested` if you placed it in `NS` and just wrapped around everything in 
    # NestedSamplers.jl
    AbstractMCMC.sample_init(rng, nested_model, spl.nested, N)
end
```", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 8, 0, 42, 41, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'cpfiffer', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467338991, 'comment_body': 'This way you forward everything to `NestedSamplers.jl` to do all the work.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 8, 0, 42, 58, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'cpfiffer', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467339057, 'comment_body': 'Scratch that, you should probably put the `Nested` struct in `NSState`, since `Nested` is mutable and seems to be modified pretty heavily.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 8, 0, 43, 28, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'cpfiffer', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467339154, 'comment_body': "See comment below -- just make a `Nested` struct and stick it as a field in `NSState`. pr_body: This PR implements the random staggering proposal algorithm to NestedSamplers.jl. A new live point is proposed by random staggering away from an existing live point. This differs from the random walk proposal in that the step size here is exponentially adjusted to reach a target acceptance rate during each proposal, in addition to between proposals.

[{'comment_id': 467337881, 'comment_body': 'No need to duplicate all these fields, just make `NS` wrap around `Nested` from [here](https://github.com/TuringLang/NestedSamplers.jl/blob/19f5273b25a5eb3a6b1278f98a1dacf5b302acb0/src/staticsampler.jl#L3).', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 8, 0, 35, 1, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'cpfiffer', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467338316, 'comment_body': 'To answer your comment: The sampler state is where you store state information for the sampler, whatever that could mean. In this case it looks like you only need `vi`, which is provided by the default sampler state here: https://github.com/TuringLang/Turing.jl/blob/614f593424f54f458f992ebe81454c29215f28fc/src/inference/Inference.jl#L528

You can remove this `NSState` stuff and just use `SamplerState`.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 8, 0, 38, 18, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'cpfiffer', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467338934, 'comment_body': "You probably need almost none of this code -- it duplicates everything in `NestedSamplers`. You should redo this to just do something like

```julia
function AbstractMCMC.sample_init!(    
	
Attach files by dragging & dropping, selecting or pasting them.
    rng::AbstractRNG,
    model::Model,   ## check `NestedModel`?
    spl::Sampler{<:NS},    ## `Nested{T,B}` ## s == spl ## or `Sampler{<:NS{space, T, P, B}}`
    N::Integer,
    verbose::Bool=true,
    resume_from=nothing,
    debug::Bool = false;
    kwargs...
) where {T, P, B}
    # You need to make a `NestedModel` somehow
    # spl.nested is what I imagine you'd call `Nested` if you placed it in `NS` and just wrapped around everything in 
    # NestedSamplers.jl
    AbstractMCMC.sample_init(rng, nested_model, spl.nested, N)
end
```", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 8, 0, 42, 41, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'cpfiffer', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467338991, 'comment_body': 'This way you forward everything to `NestedSamplers.jl` to do all the work.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 8, 0, 42, 58, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'cpfiffer', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467339057, 'comment_body': 'Scratch that, you should probably put the `Nested` struct in `NSState`, since `Nested` is mutable and seems to be modified pretty heavily.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 8, 0, 43, 28, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'cpfiffer', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467339154, 'comment_body': "See comment below -- just make a `Nested` struct and stick it as a field in `NSState`. Don't duplicate all this code. Rely on `NestedSamplers.jl` code as much as possible.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 8, 0, 44, 6, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'cpfiffer', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467339556, 'comment_body': 'None of this is necessary. If you are correctly returning a `Transition`, the rest of Turing will handle this for you.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 8, 0, 47, 3, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'cpfiffer', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467339672, 'comment_body': 'Each `step!`, you should be extracting whatever the values are inside `NestedTransition` and putting them inside `spl.state.vi`, and then returning `vi(spl)`.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 8, 0, 47, 50, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'cpfiffer', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 471048571, 'comment_body': "This needs to be Turing's model struct, `DynamicPPL.Model`, though you can usually write this as just `Model` since it's imported explicitly. Note that in the ESS implementation, we simply create a wrapper around the package's special function: https://github.com/TuringLang/Turing.jl/blob/02fae08653f07a9157808eb1f028b8a3ad4d06fb/src/inference/ess.jl#L88

This goes pretty much everywhere in the code -- you need to working with Turing's model struct, not the NestedSamplers.jl model.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 16, 0, 38, 49, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'cpfiffer', 'type': 'User'}]

I will revert it.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 29, 19, 26, 20, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'SaranjeetKaur', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 462540013, 'comment_body': 'Done!', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 29, 19, 35, 57, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'SaranjeetKaur', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 462637183, 'comment_body': "In general it's a pretty bad idea to have `try`/`catch` inside a numerical routine, especially since any error is never reported (there's no rethrow or print or anything).", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 29, 22, 57, 57, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'cpfiffer', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 462637485, 'comment_body': "It might be nice if we assigned this to a different value than `u_in`, since we're overwriting an array with just a single value and it's a little confusing.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 29, 22, 58, 47, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'cpfiffer', 'type': 'User'}]
